%U A395761 32500,34113,37500,38117,41132,41182,42262,42500,43155,43200,43392,45484,52117,52377,52500
%N A395761 Grand-kangaroo numbers: kangaroo numbers whose inner number is itself a kangaroo number (A395720).
%C A395761 All terms with q digits can be constructed from divisors of b*10^(q-1) + d where 1 <= b <= 9 and 0 <= d <= 9. - _David A. Corneth_, May 15 2026
%H A395761 David A. Corneth, <a href="/A395761/b395761.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10324</a> (first 2307 terms from Carole Dubois, terms <= 10^19)
%H A395761 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A395761/a395761.py.txt">Python program for OEIS A395761</a>
%H A395761 David A. Corneth, <a href="/A395761/a395761.gp.txt">PARI program</a>
%H A395761 Carole Dubois, <a href="/A395761/a395761.jpg">Graph</a>
%H A395761 Mickaël Launay, <a href="https://www.lemonde.fr/sciences/article/2026/04/18/nombres-kangourous-l-enigme-maths-du-monde-n-97_6681126_1650684.html">Nombres kangourous, l’énigme maths du « Monde » nᵒ 97</a>.
%e A395761 701622 is a term since it is a multiple of 162 (701622 = 162 * 4331) and 162 (kangaroo number) is itself a multiple of 6 (162 = 6 * 27).
%e A395761 The 5-digit terms can be constructed from divisors of numbers b*10^(5-1) + d where 1 <= b <= 9. One of these numbers is 10005. Its divisors are 1, 3, 5, 15, 23, 29, 69, 87, 115, 145, 345, 435, 667, 2001, 3335, 10005. We look for divisors that are > 109 and have at most 5-2 digits. These are 115, 145, 345, 435, 667. Of these only 115 is divisible by their joey. So 10005 + 10*115 = 11155 is a term. - _David A. Corneth_, May 15 2026
%t A395761 kangQ[k_] := k > 99 && With[{m = FromDigits@ IntegerDigits[k][[2 ;; -2]]}, m > 0 && Divisible[k, m]];
%t A395761 q[k_] := k > 9999 && kangQ[k] && kangQ[FromDigits@ IntegerDigits[k][[2 ;; -2]]];
%t A395761 Select[Range[10000, 52500], q] (* _Amiram Eldar_, May 05 2026 *)
%o A395761 (Python)
%o A395761 def kangaroo(n): return n > 99 and (joey:=int(str(n)[1:-1])) and n%joey == 0
%o A395761 def ok(n): return n > 9999 and kangaroo(n) and kangaroo(joey:=int(str(n)[1:-1]))
%o A395761 print([k for k in range(10**5) if ok(k)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, May 05 2026
%o A395761 (Python) # see linked program to produce b-file
